{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893774/1930102402/0435.xml":{"full_text":"\u00ae|f Iroumsuflle HernlD\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second -class matter tn the Poatofflce,\nBrownsville. Texas\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively emitted to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also tte\nlocal news published herein.\nSubscription Rates\u2014Dally and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year .$9.00\nSix Months. 14.50\nThree Months $2225\nOne Month .75\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas, Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City, Mo., 306 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago, 111., Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue,\nEL Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles, Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n846 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco. Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nBrownsville Has:\n1. A population in 1930 of 22,050.\n2. A mean average temperature of 73.\n3. Bank deposits, 522,000,000.\n4. Four railroads, seven paved highways.\n5. International airport, five air lines.\n6. A $6,000,000 deep water port finsneed.\n7. The best climate, soil in the world.\nSpeaking of Back to the Farm\nAccording to census figures on April 1st there were\n6,297,877 farms in the United States, or 73.763 less\nthan the 6,371.640 in 1925 or 150.446 less than the\n6,448,343 farms In 1920. The decrease in five years\nhaving been 12 per cent and for ten years 2 3 per\ncen. Texas, one of the banner agriculture states,\nshowed a steady increase of fr.rms over the ten years,\nhowever. In 1930 there were 496.997 farms compared\nto 465,646 in 1925 and 436,033 in 1920. Increase over\nthe ten years amounted to 59.974 or 138 per renf.\nTexas was the third state in the rate of increase\nbeing led by Arizona and California. A farm, for cen\nsus purposes, includes all lands which is directly\nfarmed by one person, either by his own labor alone\nor with the assistance of members of his household\nor hired employes. Anv tract of land less than\nthree acres used for agriculture purposes which pro\nduced products to the value of $250 in the preceding\ncalendar ypar is classed a farm.\nA favorite sating of the old Alcalda. \"Civilization\nbegins and ends with the plow\" did not lose its stg- j\nnificance when the machine age was ushered in \"away I\ndown here in Texas\nTexas Club Women Urged to Vote\nFor Amendments\nThere is an important election coming and there\nare five nending amendments to the constitution\nTexas club women are qualified voters Mrs. R. F\nLindsay is the president of the Texas Federation of\nWomen's Clubs. In a pointed address to the women\nvoters of Texas Mrs. Lindsay calls for support at the\npolls of the amendments as a civic duty; that the\namendment enabling the supreme court to hold ses\nsions at any time has long been needed; that the\nmeasure permitting the taxing of university lands by\nthe counties in which they are situated meets a just\nneed; that the one broadening the investment field\nfor university funds will lareelv increase the income\nof the institution. Her recommendation is that the\nvoters of the commonwealth, both men and women,\nwill not be negligent of the civic duty that good citi\nzenship imposes upon them, \"but will vote without\nregard to party or factional differences in support\nof these wholesome changes\nIt is estimated that 450.000 Texas women are quali\nfied voters. It is lo be hoped that vast numbers will\ngo to the polls on election daw and cast ballots in\nsupport of the \"wholesome changes.\"\nDabney White on Drouth Relief\nDabnrv White is a well known citizen, a native\nTexan, an outstanding citizen and Tyler is his place\nof residence. He completed his trek covering the\ndrouth affected part of Texas, hammered the facts\nInto copy for a newspaper in order to show \"public\nofficials particularly, the necessity for extending fi\nnancial relief to the many thousands who have lost\nmillions of dollars as the result of the recent lack of\nrain in Texas Forty years ago Dabney White, lifj\ncollege days over, was a ranger in what is knowm\nas West Texas. Covering 19 counties in the section\nwhere he served as a ranger investigator, White\nwrites that Red Cross agencies alone have reported\n9400 farm families must secure crop reduction loans\nwhile 3100 of these families are now charity cases.\n\nProceeding along the same line of information\nWriter White says, \"in addition to these institutions\nhundreds of communities will be called upon for urban\nrelief for their idle people made so by their crop fail\nures. A Red Cross agency at Spur is providing a local\nfund of $500 a month for their local charities. This\nis the conclusion of the former ranger, widely known\nin business and newspaper circles of the Southwest,\nTexas government can and must help its helpless\ncreators as much as Texans ire now asking the na\ntional government to contribute in credit facilities.\nHeretofore Texas has never permitted her people to\nsuffer from lack of food or raiment.\u201d\nWhy should Texas permit \"her people\u201d to suffer\nfrom lack of food and raiment? Those who are\nwithout collateral or credit will be enabled to borrow\nmoney from government credit banks or any other\nbanks. These unfortunates and their dependent ones j\nmust be carried through the winter by Red Cross\nagencies and the more fortunate of their fellow citi\nzens in all sections of Texas, rural as well as urban\ncircles.\nPresident Hoover has appointed a general commit\ntee to work with the governors of states and local\ncommittees. Well, winter is almost here. Local aid\nfor local victims of the drouth must be cared for by\nlocal agencies. Talk is cheap, but it takes hard cash\nto buy provisions and to provide shelter for the shel\nterless ones. Texas is one of the richest of American\ncommonwealths. It is a matter of record that 68\nper cent of its farm population are tenants. They\nwere bom in poverty. They are in debt more or less\nfrom the cradle to the grave. They are the principal\nsufferers in the drouth sections of Texas and all other\nagricultural iommonwealths of the South and the\nSouthwest.\nMorrow Makes His Declaration\nA many sided man is Dwight W. Morrow, republican\ncandidate for the office of United States senator in\nthe state of New Jersey. He was born on a farm. A?\nan early age he became a bread-winner. He fought\nfor an education. He won it by his own efforts.\nTime rolled on and the farm boy became an eminent\nfinancier, a trusted member of the house of Morgan,\nan authority on international banking, a leader of\nthe republican party, a friend and adviser of American\npresidents, an ambassador to the republic of Mexico,\nan adventurer in American politics, a candidate for\nthe primary nomination for senator on a remarkable\nplatform calling for the repeal of the 18th amend-\nment.\nHe swept every county in New Jersey, receiving a\nmajority in the stalwart dry counties. For months\nand months, since his remarkable victory at the polls,,\nhe has been the political sensation of America. He\nhas made his opening speech in the campaign of the\nyear. He will not be a candidate for the republican\npresidential nomination in 1932. In that opening\nspeech he reiterated his advocacy of the repeal of the j\n18th amendment and he eliminated himself as a\ncandidate for the presidency in the coming election\ntw years hence. He commended warmly President\nHoover and the national administration and con- j\neluded, \u201cI look forward with pleasure and confidence\nto the opportunity of voting two years from now for\nthe renomination and re-election of Herbert Hoover.\nHe eulogized the president to the highest degree, j\nHe declared Hoover stands today a potent and positive\nfactor for peace at home and abroad.\nHe declared the distressed cure for business depres- 1\nsion is with the people. His words: \u2018The most ef\nfective cure for hard times rests with the people\nthemselves and every employer who maintains his\nplant and his organization is making a substantial\ncontribution to the return of prosperity.\u201d He made j\nanother declaration that national prohibition was and\nis not an issue in his senatorial campaign and there\nthis many sided man made a mistake or rather a\nmisstatement. He advocated the repeal cf the 18t?i\namendment. It is a political issue in many American\ncommonwealths and it will remain a political issue\nfor years and years to come.\n_\nMarriages and Divorces for a\nSingle Year\nAn interesting preliminary report on the 1929\nmatrimonial statistics issued by the federal depart\nment of congress shows matrimony claimed 1.232.559\ncouples in the United States in 1929 while during the\nsame period 201.475 divorces were recorded. There\nwere 63.173 marriages and 18.386 divorces in Texas, j\nIndeed according to the report numerically Texts j\nled in divorces. Illinois second. Ohio third. California\nfourth. Georgia and the lowest proportion of di\nj vorces to marriages and New York reported most\nmarriaees. All in all the year 1929 was a busy vcir\nfor divorce court Judges.\nOur Boarding House By Ahern\nIm-----!\nI Mad Yo syAll^oU mssed a -them yht\nQl/\u00a3R-liME AY YH OEFlCE B\u00ab3 PELY-LAUgH MAYoR MAD\nBuY yeell. ME Hou! -^YH7 MAYoR Mad Y^ goYo yH\u2019\nDID *YHAY SCHEME OT^ j \"SAJUTTV TACjAM. MooZEGOVd\nYH\" MAYoRls PAM CUY? LEAMfMG AGA/MsY\nwMere Me Had a pal h AYree7 wHem\nTRQM YH\u2019 GUILTY CLUB A CC^P CAME.\nBYAMD Across YhT SYREEYl ALoMCj AaTYgoK\n50 YMAY wMeM YH\" Usui )M/M Yo YH7 SYlR\nMVsifeRious boarder suspiciomj\nwould peek: ouY YM\u2019 L\nWIMDOLi >ME7P\nYMiuk Me\nwas beimg y\n_\nr\nBEGIN HERE TODAY\nAdventure enters the life of Celia\nMitchell, 17, when she learns the\nfather she has supposed dead is\nalive and wealthy. She leaves her\nunpretentious home -n Baltimore\nto live in New' York with her father, j\nJohn Mitchell, and her aristocratic\ngrandmother.\nMargaret Rogers, Celia's mother,\nis now a w'idow, having divorced\nMitchell and later remarried. Bar\nney Shields, young newspaper\nphotographer, is in love with the\ngirl and before leaving Baltimore\nCelia promised to be loyal to his\nlove.\nMitchell asks Evelyn Parsons,\nbeautiful widow, to introduce the\ngirl to young people. Mrs. Parsons\nagrees, considering Celia a means to\nwin Mitchell s affections though she\nis jealous and at once begins schem\ning to get rid of the girl. She in\ntrouces Celia to Tod Jordan, fas\ncinating but dubious character, and\ndoes all she can to encourage the\nmatch.\nLisi Duncan, socially prominent,\nbecomes Celias loyal friend. Mitch\nell learns Jordan is paying his\ndaughter attentions and forbids her\nto see him. Celia offends her grand\nmother and the elderly Mrs. Mitch\nell feigns illness and departs for a\nrest. The girl goes to Mrs. Parsons'\nLong Island home for a lengthy vis\nit. There Jordan calls frequently.\nHe and Celia go on a picnic with\nLisi and Dicky Caruthers. Before\nthey return Mitchell arrives and\nMrs. Parsons believes he is about to\npropose.\nNOW GO ON WITH THE STORY\nCHAPTER XXXI\nIt was a magic moment. Evelyn\nParsons stood with her face half\naverted from Mitchell. In the white\nmoonlight she seemed like a goddess\n\u2014unearthly and unattainable. Not\nby the slightest movement did Eve\nlyn betray her quickening pulse.\nMitchell hesitated as though he\nwas shocked at his own daring.\nSlowly she turned her head, rais\ning her eyes to meet his. This was\nno goddess! Evelyn's gaze held ten\nderness. warmth and the suggestion\nof veiled mystery.\n\u201cI wonder,\u201d she said softly. \u201cIf I\ndo know, John?\u201d\n\u201cOh, Evelyn\u2014you're so beautiful!\"\nThe man's voice was choking with\nemotion Mrs. Parsons did not\nsmile. Had she overplayed that\nmoment of delay? Surely not. In\nanother Instant John Mitchell was\ngoing to ask her to be his wife\nHe took both her hands in his\nMitchell's eyes were earnest, anx\nious.\n\u201cYou must have known how I feel\nabout you.\u201d he said. \u201cYou\u2019ve been\nso helpful, so understanding! Eve\nlyn. you\u2019re wonderful. You're the\none woman\u2014\u201d\nThe sentence was never finished.\nSomeone was coming through the:\nliving room and at the sound of\nfootsteps both Mitchell and Mrs\nParsons turned.\n\"Oh, here you are!\u201d Celia Mltch\nrll stood in the open French win\ndow', the light from the room be\n>ond throwing her slim figure in\nsilhouette. \u201cIt\u2019s too perfect to be\nindoors, isn\u2019t it?\u201d\nShe stepped out on the porch and\ncame to join them. Celia apolo\ngized for being absent when her\nfather arrived. She chattered about\nthe picnic, hoping to forestall ques-\ntinning. No one appeared interest\ned.\nMrs. Parsons, after the first star\ni\ntied glance at the girl was unusuallj\nsilent. Mitcheli. looking embar\nrassed, listened to Celia and nov\nand then made obvious attempts at\nconversation.\nPresently Evelyn Parsons excused\nherself and went Into the house\nNot for another moment could sh\ncontain her anger. Evelyn mount\ned the stairs, hurried to her roon\nand closed the door behind her.\nShe stood leaning against it. hci\nhands clenched ana her body quiv\nering. Evelyn's eyes were closed\nher mouth a cruel sliver of crim\nson.\nOh.\u201d she gasped. \u201cOh\u2014!\u201d\nSuddenly the woman was a tor\nnado of energy. She picked up a\nbook, the first object to touch he\nhand, and hurled it across the room\nPapers, magazines, a cigaret cas\nwere next When the room looke<\nas though a windstorm had struc!\nIt. Evelyn flung herself in a chaii\nHer face was white and distorted\nOne white satin toe tapped th<\nfloor furiously.\n\nGradually she became quieter\nBlind anger gave way to an expres\nsion of grim deliberation. Evelyn'\n\u2022eyes narrowed Nothing had beei\nlost and on the whole she migh\ngain from the situation. Tempor\nary obstacles often increased a man\nardor. Hadn't she played the gam'\nfrequently?\nSne moved to her dressing tab!'\nand began working with cosmetic;\nas she framed a course of action\nIn a few moments traces of thi\ntempestuous outburst had been re\nmoved. A subtle touch of eye\nshadow made her eyes more bril\nliant and gave them a hint o\nwistfulness. She drew fresh lip:\nwith a stick of carmine, dusted he\nface and shoulders with fragran\npowder. Under lamplight these re\nstoratives would pass unnoticed.\nThe action soothed Evelyn a\nnothing else could have done. Wher\nshe had finished she surveyed her\nself with satisfaction. Like othei\nvain women Evelyn Parsons fell\nfortified by her beauty and thoughi\nno man could resist it.\nShe would make Mitchell ask\nher to marry him tomorrow. Oh\nyes. she could do that! It hac\nbeen exasperating to have the goa\nwithin reach and then rudeh\nsnatched away, but there would be\nno such slip tomorrow.\nBack in Evelyn Parsons\u2019 mind\nwas the thought that Celia would\npay for this interference. Anyone\nwho interfered with the widow's\nplans was quite likley to pay.\nShe was singing softly the re\nfrain of an Enelish ballad as she\nreturned to the porch. It was a\nsong Evelyn had heard Mitchell\nsav he was fond of\n\"Hilda's bringing something cool\nto drink.\u201d she said \u201cI thought It\nwould be refreshing.\u201d\n\u201cIsn't Evelyn the nerfect host\ness. father?\u201d Celia said. \"She nevei\nforgets anything\u201d\n\"You\u2019re quite right.\u201d Mitchel\nagreed His eyes swept Mrs. Par\nsons as she sank gracefully into s\nwicker chair. She had chosen a\nseat where th#> path of light from\nthe living room touched her hail\nand made it a golden halo.\nThe maid appeared bearing a\ntray of tall glasses and pitcher in\nwhich ice clinked invitingly. She\nThe Main Stem\nIntimate Glimpses of the Valley\u2019s Alley\nBY J. R.\nAlong Elisabeth Another Friday and Football flames Kolb\nthe Rodent Returns And Argues\nAutomobiles.Too Much.\ntl._L.tL I ___t_a e<_\u00ab a t\nMary Emma Vivier\u2014\u201ccleaning\nhouse Thursday_talking to Dr\nCharlie Calderon! demist with\noffices on the same floor of the\nState National Bank building.\nJno C. Fanning manager of the\nCapitol theater\u2014telling Doc Os\nborne that he wanted to be a\ntrapeze performer when he was a\nsmall boy Tom Stevenson_of\nthe motor company bearing his!\nname-has been in business here\nfor eight years going on nine_\nbusiness is good, he says_Mrs.\nM. P. Stephens..lunching alone.,\nat the Cameron Hotel Coffee Shop\nErnest Fernandez insurance\napproaching a prospect.\nRalph Schmclling... .onetime bank\ner. onetime hotel manager rid\ning along in a big sedan_on the\nmain stem.Ralph H. Desmond\ntemporary weather chief_\npredicting cooler weather.says\nW J. Schnurbusch. weather chief.\nwill return in a week or so-Mr\nSchnurbusch has been absent or\nvacation Alfonso Escalante.\nsteward of the Brownsville Country\nClub wearing a glaringly red tie\n-Alfonso claims that red ties\nare his weakness.\n\nAnother Fridav\nAnother week has rolled bv. and\nhere it is Friday again. Football\nat Tucker Field. Brownsville vs\nLaredo, is the main attraction to\nday.\nTomorrow, still another game.\nBrownsville College vs. Edinburr\nCollege, for the championship of\nValley colleges, will be played a!\nthe same field. There is stronp\nrivalry between Brownsville and\nEdinburg, and a large crowd Is\nexpected.\nAnd Brownsville High plays its\nfirst game with today\u2019s foe. Last\nj Stickler Solution\nThe above diagram shows how\nsix pens, of equal size, are cqn*\u2018\nstructed with the remaining twelve\nmatches.\nk I\nwrir aruim\nthe world on fire, Laredo forfeited\nthe game, refused to play.\nWe hope that when the fma\nwhistle blows today, they will wusl\nthat they had forfeited a seconc\ntime.\nQuien Sabe.\n\nKollo the Rodent\nhello\none sure way to determine\nthe financial condition of\na section is to notice the\nautomobiles, believe it or\nnot but\nif you see a main street\nlined with straight-eights\nit doesn't mean that the\ntown is on the verge of\nbankruptcy, have you seen\nany photographs i* cntly of\nthe business district of any\ntown approximately the same\nsize as Brownsville question mark\nwell, we saw one yesterday, and\nthe street was lined with model\nt fords and ancient Chevrolet*,\nthen we glanced down the mair\nstem\nhere and what did we see\u2014three\nCadillacs, a coupe of packards,\nchryslers, nashes, buicks, mar\nmons.\npterce-arrows. etc. etc. of course\nthere were plenty of fords and\nchevrolets\nbut just the same the number of\nbig\nchariots was very satisfactory\nwho says the valley is on the blink\nquestion mark,\nrollo.\nft\nToa Much\nWe\u2019ve heard of over-playing a\nhand, but this story takes the\nchocolate cake.\nA bashful suitor had to Interview\nhis prospective father-in-law. and\nasUed a friend of his to accompan;\nhim and aid in convincing the In\nlaw that he was the man for the\ngal.\nThe father was Inquisitive. \u201cDc\nyou have any land?\u201d\n\"Well, yes, some,\u201d the suitor an\nswered.\nSay, he has plenty of lanff.'\nspoke up the Big Help. \"He ha*\nabout 40 acres of beautiful land.\u201d\n\"Do you have any cattle?\u201d\n\"Some, yes.\u201d\n\"Say, he has 50 head of the\nprettiest cattle you ever saw.\u201d\nThis continued for about ter\nminutes.\n\u201cI see you have a slight cough.\u201d\n\"Yes. a slight cough.\u201d\n\u201cSlight cough nothing! He ha.<\nconsumption.\u201d was the final an\niwrer from the friend.\nr j\n8u\u00abm& i\nCRAKAER\n5 OoRNJ 1\ni DOLAki.\nH\u00a3R\u00a3Vl\n1\n.'IVl* eP\\RiT MESSAGES JRw\u2019lu^'\nu. m. p*t orr, o\u00bbmo \u00bbv wia wwct. me..\nserved the beverage, then with\ndrew.\n\u201cYou dont know how often I\nthink of this porch afternoons and\nevenings when I'm in town,\" Mitch\nell spoke up \u201cIts a great place\nyou\u2019ve got here. Evelyn.\"\n\u201cCelia and I live out here. Don't\nre. dear?\"\n\u201cAlmost. Here and in the gra\nden.\"\n\"A man\u2019s a fool to tie himself\ndown in a city all his life!\" John\nMitchell said this as though he\nwere arguing with himself. He\nbalanced his glass absent mindedly\nand the fragile crystal was in im-\nminent peril. He remembered Just\nin time.\n\u201cI don't think you ought to stay\nin town during this hot weather,\u201d\nCelia said firmly.\ni \u201cOh\u2014utterly impossible to get!\nj away\u2014now. Besides. *ee how I I\nimpose on Mrs. Parsons' hospi\ntality!\"\n\u201cYou know you could never do i\nthat, John.\" Evelyn spoke in a j\nlow tone. She save Mitchell a\nquick glance, then her eyes turned\naway.\nFor nearly an hour the three sat\n(enjoying the breeze and the fan\ntastic pattern of light and shadows\nwoven on the moonlit dawn. Then\nMitchell said it was time for him\nto go. He was spending the night\nat the country club and promised\nto rejoin them next day after his\nmorning round of golf.\n\nHe departed Celia paused long\nenough in the upstairs hallway be\nfore going to her room to say to\nMrs Parsons:\n\u2018You looked perfectly beautiful\ntonight. Evelyn! I thought at firs:\nyou'd done your hair a different\nwav. but it isn't that I guess it\u2019s\njust because you really are beauti\nful!\"\n\u201cSilly child. Tell me about the\ni picnic\n\u201cIt was fun Listen. Evelyn, do\nvou think vou'll be able to talk to\nfather tomorrow about Tod? I\nmean about getting him to change\nhis opinion of him? It sort of\nbothers me I can't help but wor\nry\u2014\"\nSheer Inspiration prompted Eve\nj Ivn Parsons. An eager light came\ninto her eyes.\n\u2018I\u2019ll do what I can Ce\u2019ia.\" she\nsaid. \u201cAnd I'm sure I can't fail.\nLet's see\u2014the thing is to manage\nthis the right way.\"\nShe studied silently a moment.\n\u201cI know!\" she continued, \u201cWell\npretend you have an errand to\nmorrow afternoon after luncheon\nYou can take the car and stay away\na long time\u2014two hours at least!\nThat will give me the chance to\nhave the sort of talk with your fa\nther wherP I can lead up to the\nsubject. Don't you cee? First I'll\ntalk about how popular you are at\nthe club and how everyone likes\nvou. That w\u2019ill be sure to start\nhim on his plans for your future.\nFrom that it will be no trick at all\nfor me to mention Tod and what a\nsplendid young man he is.\"\n\u201cOh. Evelyn!\"\nThe girl was delighted\n\u201cThat's how we'll manage it Now\nremember your part is to go for a\nlong drive that will give me plenty\nof time\u2014\"\n\u201cI\u2019ll time myself.'* Celia assured\nher \u201cI'll give you hours! Good\nnight. Evelyn.\"\n\u201cGood night, dear!\"\nAs Evelyn Parsons closed the door\nof her room she was convinced that\nfate was her ally.\n\nCelia was trying to learn tennis.\nThe game fascinated her, and Lisi\nDuncan, who played expertly, had\nvolunteered some instruction.\nCelia was too shy to expose her\nfeeble efforts on the courts at the\nclub, but she could bounce balls\nagainst the backstops on the court\nat Larchwood to her heart's con- i\ntent.\nShe was in the midst of an exclt-1\ning private practice Sunday morn- j\ning when she heard her father's\nvoice.\n\u201cHigher!\" he called. \u201cThrow the\nbafl higher in the air before you\nstrike it.\u201d\nI The girl turned in the direction\nfrom where his voice came. Mitch\nell stood in the pathway through\nthe hedge. His hands were on his\nhips. He might have been watch- J\ning her for some time.\nHer face, red from exertion, col-\nored more darkly.\n\u201cI didn't see you.\" she said. \u201cGood\nmorning. I\u2019m afraid I'll never learn\nhow to serve!\"\n\u201cYou don\u2019t throw the ball high\nenough,\u201d Mitchell repeated. He\nwalked out to where she stood, took\nthe racket and ball In his own\nhands. \u201cHere, like this!\u201d\nThe white sphere cut sharply\nacross the net to the opposite cor\nner of the court.\n\u2022Perfect!\u201d cried Celia.\n*T haven\u2019t had a tennis racket in\nmy hands for years.\u201d her father\nsaid, looking down at the object.\nGetting too old for the game.\u201d\nNot when you can serve a ball\nlike that! Oh, I wish 1 could make\nthem spin that way! Mine wont\neven go over the net,\u201d\nHave you got another racket?\u201d\n\u201cThere are some in the house.\nWait\u2014I\u2019ll be back in two minutes!\u201d\nCelia turned and sped down the\npathway. In a short time she was\nback, breathless and e.'ges shining.\nShe carried three tennis rackets.\n\u201cHelp yourself,\u201d Celia urged.\nMitchell tried them, selected one\nand walked to the opposite side of\nthe net. He had already put aside\nhis coat and hat. For some time\nhe returned balls and called out\nsuggestions as Celia practiced. Lat\ner they were opponents in a game.\nIt ended in the man\u2019s favor. They\nplayed a second which Celia wori.\nand then her father demanded time\nout for rest\nThe girl\u2019s embarrassment was\ngone. She asked questions, tried to\ncorrect faults Mitchell criticized.\n\u2019You'll get along all right,\u201d he as\nsured her. \u201cIt comes with practice.\"\nCelia brushed her hair back im\npatiently. In her short white dress\nand heelers slippers she looked a\nchild. Sunshine had turned her\nface and arms a ruddy tan.\nA low exclamation came from\nJoin Mitchell.\n\u201cCompletely forgot!\u201d he said em\nphatically. Sorry. Celia. I brought\na letter down to you yesterday and\nforgot to give it to you. Now where\ndid I put that\u2014\u201d\nHe began to search his pockets.\n(To Be Continued*\nFifty men were arrested In Ok\nlahoma in the last fiscal year on\nbank robbery charges. Twenty-sev\nen were convicted and sentenced,\ni two were killed and 17 await trial.\nNorth Carolina elementary school\nchildren borrowed 1,500.000 books\nfrom 385 standard libraries las*,\nyear.\nEat Those Good\nPECAN WAFFLES\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St. Phone 983\nIn not a matter of quantity,\nbat of REGULARITY. It re\nsides in the often-proved axi\nom that LITTLE makes RIG.\nThe daily taifUlmet of hopes\nfreedom from worry\nearly financial independence\nand contented old age\nmay be YOURS, by making\neasy treek-to-week deposits at\nWOOD and DODD\n(Insurance Surety Bonds\nSpivey-Kowalski Bldg. Phone 100\nBROWNSVILLE\nI\u2022j!\nDependable Phone 353 Prompt\nBROWNSVILLE TITLE COMPANY\nBROWNSVILLE. TEXAS\nAbstracts Title Insurance\nWe Cover All Lands In Cameron County\nI AZTEC CAFE\n\n7\nCorner Eleventh and Market Square\nWILL OPEN FRIDAY, OCT. 24 j\nji MEXICAN COOKING A SPECIALTY\nI\nOn opening day coffee and tamales will be served FREE\nj; from 3 to 5 o\u2019clock p. m. A cordial invitation extended to\nthe public to visit us. assuring you courteous and prompt\nservice at reasonable prices.\n\nMRS. V. F. MARRON. Manager\ni 2\nrrfffftrffififff---\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS","height":"37152","width":"28156"}}
